---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="About | Andrew Lukosevic">
  <article>
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-neutral-100">About</h1>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Writing one of these is harder than it should be. You'd think after years of writing detections
        and threat reports I could describe myself in a few paragraphs, but here we are.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        I'll do my best.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">The Short Version</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I'm Andrew. I lead threat hunting and detection engineering at
        <a href="https://www.sentinelone.com" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">SentinelOne</a>.
        I live near Nashville, Tennessee. I like to read, run, lift heavy things, and chase game through
        the woods. I'm building an AI system in my spare time because apparently I don't believe in rest days.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">What I Do</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I hunt threats for a living. Not the kind where you sit and wait for alerts to fire—the kind
        where you go looking for adversaries who are already inside and haven't tripped anything yet.
        That's the work I find most interesting: finding the stuff that automated systems miss.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I didn't start there. I started where most people in cybersecurity start—as a SOC analyst,
        L1, watching dashboards at odd hours. From there I moved into SIEM engineering, then back to
        the analyst side as an L2, then incident response, then leading an IR team. Eventually I
        ran a SOC before landing on threat hunting, which is where I should've been all along.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        Along the way: AT&T, LevelBlue, now SentinelOne. Each job sharpened a different edge. But
        the through-line was always the same—I'd rather go find the problem than wait for it to find me.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">What Drives Me</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I like doing hard things because they're hard. That's not a bumper sticker—it's genuinely
        how I'm wired. If something is uncomfortable or difficult, there's a good chance I'm going
        to lean into it instead of away from it. Running long distances, hunting on foot, learning
        new domains, building systems from scratch. The discomfort is the point.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        I also believe in being proactive over reactive, in pretty much everything. My entire career
        arc has been a slow migration from "respond to the incident" to "find the threat before there
        is an incident." That same instinct shows up in how I train, how I hunt, how I build things.
        Don't wait. Go.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">Outside the Screen</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I'm an endurance hunter. That means I chase game on foot over long distances—no blinds,
        no tree stands, just boots and persistence. I run
        <a href="https://youtube.com/@EndurHunt" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">EndurHunt</a>
        on YouTube where I document the hunts and the lifestyle around it. There's a lot of overlap
        between tracking an adversary on a network and tracking game through timber—patience,
        pattern recognition, reading sign, and knowing when to commit.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I run and lift regularly. Not for aesthetics—for capacity. I want to be able to hike 15 miles
        in rough terrain carrying a pack without thinking about it. The gym is where that gets built.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        I read a lot. Mostly nonfiction—history, science, strategy, anything that helps me understand
        how things work. Recently I've been getting into novels, which is new territory for me. Turns
        out fiction teaches you things nonfiction can't.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">The AI Thing</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        I'm deep into AI—not as a buzzword, but as a builder. I've been developing a personal AI
        infrastructure I call PAI that sits on top of Claude Code. It's a system for magnifying
        what I can do: automating research, running multi-agent workflows, building tools. I think
        the people who learn to work <em>with</em> AI at a deep level are going to have a massive
        advantage, and I'd rather be building that muscle now than catching up later.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4 text-neutral-100">Find Me</h2>
      <ul class="text-neutral-400 space-y-2">
        <li><a href="https://x.com/awluko" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">X / Twitter</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/awluko" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">GitHub</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://linkedin.com/in/andrew-lukosevic" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">LinkedIn</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://youtube.com/@EndurHunt" class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300">EndurHunt on YouTube</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
